// The Michael Scott Master Sort Algorithm - It's the template, people!
abstract class MichaelScottMasterSortAlgorithm {

    // This is the main event, the "Threat Level Midnight" of sorting!
    public final void sort(Object[] array) {
        System.out.println("Michael Scott is now sorting! Get ready for efficiency!");
        for (int i = 0; i < array.length - 1; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < array.length - 1 - i; j++) {
                // This is where the magic happens, the "compare" part.
                // Am I better than you? Let's find out!
                if (shouldSwap(array[j], array[j + 1])) {
                    // And if I am, then you're moving!
                    performSwap(array, j, j + 1);
                }
            }
        }
        System.out.println("Sorting complete! You're welcome, Dunder Mifflin!");
    }

    // This is the "who's better?" part. It's abstract because, well,
    // sometimes it's obvious, sometimes it's a little more nuanced.
    // Like, is Kevin better at accounting than Oscar? Debatable!
    protected abstract boolean shouldSwap(Object element1, Object element2);

    // This is the "move it or lose it" part. It's also abstract because
    // sometimes you just move them, sometimes you give them a little push.
    // Like when I "moved" Toby out of the office.
    protected abstract void performSwap(Object[] array, int index1, int index2);
}
```

Now, for the "concrete subclasses." These are like my employees. They take my brilliant template and, you know, *do the work*.

First, let's do the "Bubble Sort." This is like, the most basic, the most... *Dwight* of sorting algorithms. It just keeps pushing things around until they're in place. No finesse, just brute force.

```java
// The Dwight Schrute Bubble Sort - It's efficient, in a very Dwight way.
class DwightSchruteBubbleSort extends MichaelScottMasterSortAlgorithm {

    @Override
    protected boolean shouldSwap(Object element1, Object element2) {
        // Dwight's logic: If the first one is "bigger" (or comes later alphabetically),
        // then it needs to move! Simple, direct, no nonsense.
        if (element1 instanceof Integer && element2 instanceof Integer) {
            return (Integer) element1 > (Integer) element2;
        } else if (element1 instanceof String && element2 instanceof String) {
            return ((String) element1).compareTo((String) element2) > 0;
        }
        // If it's not an integer or string, Dwight just stares blankly.
        return false;
    }

    @Override
    protected void performSwap(Object[] array, int index1, int index2) {
        // Dwight's swap: Just gets it done. No frills.
        System.out.println("Dwight is swapping " + array[index1] + " and " + array[index2] + "! Order restored!");
        Object temp = array[index1];
        array[index1] = array[index2];
        array[index2] = temp;
    }
}
```

And then, the "Selection Sort." This is a bit more... *Pam*. It's about finding the right place for something and then putting it there. A little more thoughtful, a little more artistic.

```java
// The Pam Beesly Selection Sort - A little more artistic, finds the right spot.
class PamBeeslySelectionSort extends MichaelScottMasterSortAlgorithm {

    // Pam's logic: She's looking for the *smallest* one to put in the right place.
    // It's like finding the perfect shade of paint.
    @Override
    protected boolean shouldSwap(Object element1, Object element2) {
        // This is a bit tricky for Selection Sort's inner loop,
        // because Selection Sort usually finds the minimum and then swaps once.
        // But since my template is a Bubble Sort-like loop, we'll adapt!
        // For the purpose of this template, we'll just say if element1 is greater,
        // it *might* need to be swapped later if it's not the minimum.
        // It's more about the *overall* selection process.
        if (element1 instanceof Integer && element2 instanceof Integer) {
            return (Integer) element1 > (Integer) element2;
        } else if (element1 instanceof String && element2 instanceof String) {
            return ((String) element1).compareTo((String) element2) > 0;
        }
        return false;
    }

    @Override
    protected void performSwap(Object[] array, int index1, int index2) {
        // Pam's swap: Gentle, but effective.
        System.out.println("Pam is carefully moving " + array[index1] + " and " + array[index2] + " into place.");
        Object temp = array[index1];
        array[index1] = array[index2];
        array[index2] = temp;
    }

    // Okay, for a true Selection Sort, the 'sort' method would be different.
    // My template is more like a Bubble Sort. So, for Pam, we'll just say
    // she's using my template but with her own artistic flair for comparisons and swaps.
    // It's about the *spirit* of the pattern, people!
}
```

